Citations
Date:  0/0/1940
Source:  Te Waimate
Author:  STUDHOLME
Vol / Page:  129
Edition:
Quote:  When an old hand and a young one were sharing a catching pen, the former would let the learner in for the 'cobbler' or hard shearing sheep, at the end of every pen, and when the pen had been refilled, quickly catch and shear all the 'rosellas' or easily shorn sheep, before the unfortunate novice had finished his cobbler.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1960
Source:  Back-Country Tales
Author:  MASTERS
Vol / Page:  258
Edition:
Quote:  I let him get his third sheep on the board, then grabbed the rosella, hacked the few tufts of wool off and dumped her out of the porthole.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1981
Source:  Loughnan Glossary
Author:  LOUGHNAN
Vol / Page:  67
Edition:
Quote:  rosella: a sheep that has cast most of its wool before shearing. The shearer will usually leave it until last so that he can use it for timing his catch.
